Boil a large #pot{} of water for the @butternut squash{1}(diced).

Once boiling, cook until fork tender, ~{15-18%minutes}.

Pick the @sage{5%g} leaves from their stalks and roughly chop (discard the stalks).

Once the squash is cooked, drain in a #colander{} and return to the pot, off the heat.

Add half the chopped sage, a knob of @butter{to taste} and a little @milk{to taste}(optional) or @water{to taste}. Mash with a #potato masher{} until smooth. Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}. Cover to keep warm.

Place a large pan over medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Once the oil is hot, add the @Irish pork sausages{225%g} and fry until browned and cooked through, ~{7-8%minutes}, shifting as they colour.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat. The sausages are cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Once cooked, set aside the sausages.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}.

When sausages are cooked return the (now empty) pan to the heat with a drizzle of oil.

When the oil is hot, add the sliced onions and cook for ~{3-5%minutes}.

Sprinkle in @flour{1%tbsp} and cook for ~{1%minute}.

> Double the flour for 4p.

Add @water{200%ml}, @chicken stock{1%sachet}, @Worcester sauce{1%sachet} and remaining chopped sage.

Bring to the boil then add in the cooked sausages.

Cook for another ~{3-5%minutes}, until sausages are warmed through.

Meanwhile, in a bowl for the salad mix together @salt{to taste}, @pepper{to taste} and a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Just before serving, toss the @salad leaves{40%g} in the dressing.

Divide the salad between plates and drizzle over the @balsamic glaze{1%sachet}.

Dish up the butternut mash and sausages with the onion gravy.